Name: Brown, Timothy
Remarks: An other great cause of much of the misery so prevelent in this district is owing to the numerous petty shops kept by the Irish as fuel and provision venders which in fact are no better than regular licenes grogeries as an example in Small St as well as in other streets a house is rented by Irish who occupy the front part of the downstairs and one or two other rooms the rest of the house is rented out by rooms from fifty to sevety five cents per week to colored people now the shops not only supply the black tenents with wood, coal etc but with rum also now the shopkeeper will not sell rum to everyone but only to their particular customers the miserable blacks their their beloved associates for a season.
Source: RG2/Pho vol. 3 (Southwark and Moyamensing), Friends Historical Library of Swarthmore College

Name: Jackson, Mary
Remarks: My heart is sick my soul is horrow stricken at what my eyes behold & I am ready to question whether these poor creatures are possessed (?) of rational souls. Oh! fallen man how prone art thou to sink into the lowest depths of sin & folly. Intemperance, Idleness, & adultery & every other vice that can debase a man and  sink him lower into an Abyss of misery  & crime are here the daily companions of these deluded people. Here they live for a month for a Week ah! and for a night only in the open violation of every law human & Divine of morality & virtue. Males & female indiscriminately and exaltingly imitating & practicing the vices of each other. The greater part of  these people in Small st between 5th & 6th live with Irish.
Source: RG2/Pho vol. 3 (Southwark and Moyamensing), Friends Historical Library of Swarthmore College

Name: Jackson, Wm
Remarks: Doing Well.  On Shippen street between 7th & 8th there are some very respectable colored people but, for the most part those miserable creatures are in the majority There are in this vicinity not so many as in Baker street and other places but still the number is alarming there are many here who from necessity are very destitute and doubtless would do much better if an oppertunity to do so was afforded but from the peculiar situations in which many are placed it seems almost a matter of impossibility for them to do better without the assistance of those in whose power it is to give them regular employment Another great cause of the poverty of the paupers and the Laborers is the vast and almost insurmountable rent rax, many who from being without employment this winter have had to pawn almost everything they possesed to keep up.
Source: RG2/Pho vol. 3 (Southwark and Moyamensing), Friends Historical Library of Swarthmore College
